Neither `dup` nor `clone` will do the right thing here either - there *is* one reliable way to do it, but it's (somewhat) expensive and fails if an object can't be Marshalled:
```ruby
irb: h = { a: [1,2,3], b: [4,5,6] }
===> {:a=>[1, 2, 3], :b=>[4, 5, 6]}
irb: h_copy = Marshal.load(Marshal.dump(h))
===> {:a=>[1, 2, 3], :b=>[4, 5, 6]}
irb: h_copy[:a][0] = -1
===> -1
irb: h
===> {:a=>[1, 2, 3], :b=>[4, 5, 6]}
```
There's also the side-issue that such copying would have to be done pessimistically (every time an object is loaded from the DB) or users would likely encounter bugs if they mutate the serialized attribute in-place (since calling `some_serialized_attribute_will_change!` isn't currently required by the "save serialized things every time" strategy).

